#1 Adenomatous cecal polyp
We will proceed with a complex colonoscopy after he is cleared by Cardiology to see if this can be removed endoscopically.  I discussed with him and his wife that if this does not seem to be amenable to endoscopic removal he will likely need a right hemicolectomy.  Also, if this is able to be removed but there is evidence of a malignancy, he will also need surgery.  There is a chance, if it is able to be removed endoscopically and there is no evidence of cancer, that maybe multiple complex endoscopies can remove this completely.  He would like to attempt the complex colonoscopy route prior to jumping to surgery.  He will see Dr. Ismael Montoya in surgical consultation later this week.
#2 Coronary artery disease
As he has had dyspnea on exertion and has not had a recent cardiac evaluation, we will set-up a cardiology consultation.  Our cardiology colleagues have decided to preschedule a sestamibi scan as well as an echocardiogram.  Beforehand, we will get an updated EKG.
#3 Hyperlipidemia
I will check a lipid screen, so the cardiologist can look at this as well.
#4 Diabetes mellitus type-2
Reviewed fasting instructions with him.  We will obtain a fasting glucose and hemoglobin A1c.
#5 Personal history of sigmoid cancer
I will check a CEA.
#6 Left inguinal hernia
We will consult General Surgery for an opinion.  If he requires surgery for this polyp, this would take precedence, and I discussed with the patient and his wife if this were to be the case he may have to wait six-weeks at minimum in-between the two surgeries if our general surgeons felt this was indicated.  We do have evidence of the hernia also on his outside CT-scan.
#7 Dyspnea on exertion
Discussed above.  Will have Cardiology evaluate.  This is not likely to be respiratory-related, but we will obtain a basic chest x-ray.  He has no history of tobacco use.  Likely due to cardiomyopathy and heart disease.
#8 Hypertension
Well-controlled.
#9 Questionable hemorrhoid
When Dr. Montoya sees him back, we will perform anoscopy to look in more detail at this to make sure there is not something concerning, as this is fairly new and is a little more firm than what I am used to feeling.  This does not appear to look obviously, from what I can see today, like a malignancy.
Spent 90 minutes with Dr. Keith and his wife.  I called up his hard chart and reviewed multiple records in detail.  I will plan to see him back with Dr. Montoya following his appointments including his cardiology evaluation prior to his colonoscopy, and then after his colonoscopy to see whether he will end up needing surgery for the polyp.  All questions were answered.
Code status discussed.  Dr. Keith would like to be a full code.  This was discussed in the presence of his wife.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at RCH.

